<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Views `Objective Criteria' in Dispute </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603092894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0920 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kanazawa, March 26 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa said Saturday [26 March] he will consider whether Japan 
can set up "objective criteria" as a way to slash its huge trade 
surplus with the United States. At a press conference here, 
Hosokawa said he would like to take enough time to consider 
whether it could be possible to incorporate objective criteria 
into a package of measures to cut Japan's 60 billion dollar 
trade surplus with the U.S. 
  Washington has been pressuring Tokyo to whittle down the 
lopsided trade surplus by setting up objective criteria, such as 
numerical targets to gauge foreign access to the Japanese 
market. Japan, however, is opposed to the idea, saying it would 
lead to managed trade. 
  The bilateral "framework" talks in Washington in February 
broke down due to differences over the matter. 
  As for domestic politics, Hosokawa said he wants to promote 
his plan to establish a study group within the coalition, saying 
it is important for coalition partners to fine-tune common ideas 
to fight elections. 
  Hosokawa's plan to form a study group involving all seven 
coalition parties is believed to be a preliminary stage before 
establishing a new party to fight off the leading opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party in the next general election. The 
coming election is likely to be held under a new system mixing 
single-seat constituencies and proportional representation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

