<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Conducts Poll on Hosokawa Support Rate </TI></H3>
<H4>   Approval Rate Continues Slide </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403191394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2403191394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] YOMIURI SHIMBUN conducted a nationwide public 
opinion poll on 19-20 March to determine the trend in public 
support for Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's administration. 
The results showed the Hosokawa cabinet's approval rating 
decreased 2.9 percent from last month, down to 55.1 percent. 
This was a decrease for the second consecutive month, with the 
cabinet marking its worst support rating. 
  Of the respondents, 34 percent expressed disapproval of the 
cabinet, up 4.5 percent over last month. Regarding policies 
they disapproved of, 48 percent of the respondents cited "rice 
and other farm policies," a surge of approximately 20-percent 
over last month. This indicates that the people's complaints 
regarding the rice shortage have gushed out. 
  The latest cabinet approval rating is still high in 
comparison to those of previous cabinets. The Hosokawa 
administration, which faces difficult problems, such as the 
growing discord in the ruling coalition alliance and the 
considerable delay in deliberations over the draft national 
budget for the next fiscal year, has relied heavily on its high 
approval rating to keep itself going. However, the continued 
decline seems to have dealt it a serious blow. 
  Regarding reasons for supporting the cabinet, 53 percent of 
the respondents expressed passive approval of the cabinet, 
saying "it is at least better than previous cabinets." However, 
the percent decreased as regards other reasons for supporting 
the cabinet. For example, only 18 percent said "the cabinet's 
political stance can be rated highly." 
  Ratings for the administration's policies also decreased in 
nearly all areas. For example, 34 percent of the respondents 
said they highly rated the cabinet as regards "political reform 
and political ethics." 
  As for reasons for not supporting the cabinet, 21 percent of 
the respondents said "it has accomplished nothing noteworthy," a 
marked 6-percent increase over last month. 
  As for policies disapproved of by the respondents, "rice and 
other farm policies" topped of the list, with 48 percent of the 
respondents citing it. This was followed by "economic and price 
policies" at 44 percent, and a "tax system policy" at 33 
percent. The disapproval rating for "rice and other farm 
policies" increased by 19 percent over last month. This is an 
indication of strong public disapproval over the government's 
mishandling of the rice shortage issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7553 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas060__a94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-060-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Conducts Poll on Hosokawa Support Rate </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on Poll Results </H4>
<F P=102> OW2503131394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2503131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A nationwide poll conducted by YOMIURI SHIMBUN on 
19 and 20 March shows that the percentage of those who hope "the 
Hosokawa government should be in power as long as possible" has 
drastically decreased from six months ago. On the question of 
which party they would vote for in the next general election, 
the number of those who said they would vote for the Liberal 
Democratic Party [LDP] and the Social Democratic Party of Japan 
[SDPJ] increased, while the percentage of those who would vote 
for the Japan New Party [JNP] dropped by 7 points. The results 
show signs of Hosokawa's popularity waning. 
  Asked why they think the ruling coalition was thrown into 
confusion over the plans to reshuffle the cabinet and introduce 
a national welfare tax, the pollees raised the following 
reasons: 1) Because Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] Chief 
Secretary Ichiro Ozawa exerted too much influence on the plans; 
2) because, from the beginning, it was impossible for the ruling 
parties to coordinate their opinions; and 3) because Prime 
Minister Hosokawa acted a bit arbitrarily. 
  "Asked how many years they want the Hosokawa government to 
be 
in power," 33 percent said another year, 25 percent said another 
two or three years, 19 percent said the government should step 
down from power immediately, and 17 percent hoped it would be in 
power as long as possible. The same question was posed in polls 
conducted last September, and January this year. Compared with 
the results of the September poll, the percentage of those who 
want the government to be in power "as long as possible" 
decreased by 14 points, those who said "another year" increased 
by 15 points, and those who want the government to get out of 
power immediately increased by 8 points. 
  In answering what parties they would vote for if the general 
election is conducted, 28 percent said they would vote for the 
LDP, 11 percent for the JNP, 10 percent each for Shinseito and 
the SDPJ, and 5 percent for Sakigake [Harbinger]. Compared with 
the results of the January poll, the LDP and the SDPJ gained 
about 2 to 3 points, while the JNP lost a lot. Nevertheless, 
the LDP and the SDPJ are far from the level of the approval 
ratings they obtained last June -- 31 percent and 15 percent 
respectively. The June poll was conducted immediately before 
last year's general election in which the LDP and the SDPJ were 
decidedly defeated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7554 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas060__a94012" </HT>


