<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Urges Coalition To Prepare for Election </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903002494 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2903002494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Kagoshima Prefectural headquarters of the 
Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] held a meeting in 
Kagoshima city on 26 March. On the issue of the next general 
election for the House of Representatives, Wataru Kubo, 
secretary general of the SDPJ, told the meeting: "If the 
general election were to be held before this autumn, it would be 
under the present multiseat constituency system. The ruling 
coalition parties need to prepare for their election campaign 
under any electoral system. They need to cooperate with each 
other in the next general election." 
  He indicated the need for the ruling coalition parties to 
speedily prepare themselves for electoral cooperation in 
anticipation that the next general election will be held under 
the current multiseat constituency system once the House of 
Representatives has been dissolved. 
  Commenting on moves by Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] to 
form a new party, he expressed again a negative view. 
  He said: "It will be difficult for the ruling coalition 
parties to form a new party unless they reach a general 
consensus on the view of the state, the Constitution, and 
political tactics." 

</TEXT>

