<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Stance on DPRK Nuclear Issue Examined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903050494 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Mar 93 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2903050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "SDPJ Is at Loss on How To Deal With </F>
Economic Sanctions Against North Korea"] 
  [Text] As one of the ruling coalition partners, the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] is at a loss over how to deal 
with the issue of North Korea's suspected nuclear development. 
The other ruling coalition parties have said, if the UN 
Security Council decides to impose economic sanctions on North 
Korea, "Japan should go along with them." 
  However, Chairman Murayama of the SDPJ, which has maintained 
friendly relations with the Workers' Party of Korea in North 
Korea, has said, "Japan should work for dialogue with North 
Korea rather than go along with the economic sanctions 
immediately." 
  There are concerns within the government and ruling 
coalition 
parties that a rift could be created in the coalition government 
depending on what action the SDPJ takes. 
  The UN Security Council has begun studying the possibility 
of 
imposing economic sanctions against North Korea after it refused 
to allow inspections of its nuclear facilities by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency. In response, the SDPJ, at a 
24 March meeting of its Central Executive Committee, decided to 
speedily study its strategy in dealing with the issue of North 
Korea's suspected nuclear development. 
  It is possible that, during Diet deliberations, SDPJ cabinet 
members could be asked to vote on whether U.S. Forces in Japan 
impose a naval blockade against North Korea as part of economic 
sanctions. The party, therefore, has concluded that it needs to 
shape a party consensus on the issue of North Korea's suspected 
nuclear development. 
  The SDPJ plans to announce its official view after 
collecting 
information starting early this week. People in the SDPJ are 
increasingly cautious about how to handle the issue. Secretary 
General Kubo says the party wants to "adopt a policy of dialogue 
with North Korea" on the grounds that: 1) It fears that North 
Korea might respond to external pressure by acts of terrorism; 
and 2) there is no guarantee that the imposition of economic 
sanctions against North Korea will force the country to accept 
the nuclear inspections. 
  For this reason, Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] and other 
ruling coalition parties are saying "it is difficult to predict 
whether the SDPJ will announce a responsible policy on the issue 
as a ruling party." 
  It is said the SDPJ has always been "pro-North Korea" in its 
longstanding policy on the Korean peninsula. The SDPJ 
normalized its relations with South Korea when former Chairman 
Yamahana visited that country last September. There is a 
feeling the relationship between the SDPJ and the Workers' Party 
of Korea is not in good shape. The SDPJ, however, plans to 
continue its friendly relations with the Workers' Party of 
Korea. The U.S. Congress is concerned that the "Hosokawa 
government may not be able to deal resolutely with the issue of 
North Korea's suspected nuclear development because cabinet 
members have close ties with North Korea." 
  A Shinseito source said some people in the ruling coalition 
parties are wary of the SDPJ, saying "we will have to work so as 
not to produce a useless international misunderstanding." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

