<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Defends Record in Abiding by U.S. Accords </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003054394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3003054394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
[MITI] compiled a report on the extent economic agreements and 
accords signed between Japan and the United States have been 
implemented. While the United States strongly criticizes Japan 
for "not abiding by almost all of the agreements," MITI cites 17 
concrete cases, including beef, citrus fruit, and 
supercomputers, to refute such a charge. MITI reports: 
"Imports of beef increased by 90 percent between 1988 and 1992; 
results have been achieved in many areas." Japan intends to use 
this report as data to clear up U.S. "misunderstanding" at the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks and similar bilateral 
negotiations in the future. 
  There are around 30 agreements and accords signed between 
the 
two countries. The United States has serious doubts about 
Japan's efforts to implement these agreements, as evidenced in 
President Bill Clinton's remark during the recent Japan-U.S. 
summit talks that "despite the 30-odd agreements signed, there 
has been no change at all." MITI believes: "Such a perception 
is behind the Japan-U.S. economic friction." It has, therefore, 
engaged in an assessment of Japan's performance regarding the 
agreements. 
  Aside from beef and citrus fruit, other examples cited 
include: Agreements on medical equipment and pharmaceuticals, 
forestry products, cigarettes, computers, satellites, Nippon 
Telegraph and Telephone Corporation's (NTT) procurement, auto 
parts, automobiles, paper, sheet glass, amorphous metal 
transformer, textiles, steel, and machine tools, and the 
Structural Impediments Initiative talks. 
  MITI emphasizes: "Japan abides by these agreements and 
accords, and visible results have been achieved." For example, 
in the case of beef and citrus fruit, as a result of abolishing 
import quotas, and implementing the agreement on tariffication, 
imports of beef grew by 90 percent, and imports of orange juice 
by 330 percent between 1988 and 1992. Imports of forestry 
products also increased by 250 percent between 1985 and 1992. 
In the case of auto parts, one of the focal issues at the 
framework talks, imports from the United States expanded from 
$6.1 billion in fiscal 1990 to $13.6 billion in fiscal 1992. 
  MITI "wants to use this to refute the United States." 
However, the report does not touch on semiconductors and car 
phones, which have been the controversial issues in recent 
weeks. This may give rise to criticism in the United States 
that the document merely cites examples to suit Japan's purpose. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7565 </DOCNO>
