<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leaders Consider Formation of New Party </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hosokawa Denies Reports </H4>
<F P=102> OW3003110494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Mar 
94 Evening Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3003110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a news conference on the morning of 29 March, 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa was asked about a news report 
that an agreement has been reached between Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party] Chief Secretary Ichiro Ozawa, Komeito Secretary 
General Yuichi Ichikawa, and Hosokawa that they will work to 
form a new party for which "Hosokawa would serve as 
representative and Ozawa as secretary general." In reply, 
Hosokawa denied the report, saying: "It was a complete surprise 
to me. I am greatly annoyed by that report." When asked about 
the current situation in which many reports have been circulated 
on the issue of forming a new party, Hosokawa said, "I cannot 
answer the question because I am devoted entirely to official 
business." 

</TEXT>

