<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Says Seoul To Cancel `Team Spirit' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903125294 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Mar 94 
Evening Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2903125294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Harufumi Kiyota] </F>
  [Text] Seoul, 28 Mar -- It appears that the ROK Government 
has canceled its plans to resume the 1994 "Team Spirit" military 
exercises. According to a ROK Government source, the ROK has 
adopted a principle to use the resumption of the ROK-U.S. joint 
exercises as a bargaining chip for future negotiations with the 
DPRK (North Korea) over that nation's alleged nuclear weapons 
development program. ROK Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu, who is 
now visiting China, is expected to fly directly to the United 
States to finalize the policy with such U.S. leaders as 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher and Defense Secretary 
William Perry. 
  On 28 March, a ROK Government source told an ASAHI SHIMBUN 
reporter the following: "The U.S. Forces Korea have already 
determined their deployment of Patriot missiles, and the 
decision will not be revised. As for Team Spirit, it may be 
resumed in April or May if North Korea decides to completely 
withdraw from the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT). At 
the present, however, we are undecided whether or not the 
exercises should be resumed. It depends on North Korea's future 
course of action." 
  An early resumption of Team Spirit was advocated by the ROK 
Defense Ministry when North Korea refused to fully accept 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] inspections, and the 
issue was brought to the UN Security Council. The ROK 
Presidential Office and Foreign Ministry are taking a positive 
stand toward the resumption but say that "the timing will be 
decided on in consultations with the United States after 
President Kim Yong-sam's trip to Japan and China." 
  Nevertheless, North Korea reacted strongly to such moves, 
stressing: "If Team Spirit is held and the IAEA maintains its 
unfair attitudes, we will withdraw completely from the NPT." 
  Now that the cold war has ended, Team Spirit is the United 
States' biggest exercise featuring emergency operations and 
field battles. To cope with the exercise, North Korea has 
always activated its armed forces and conducted large-scale 
exercises as counteractions. Moreover, even the general public 
had to put up with evacuation exercises and blackouts. Thus, 
Team Spirit has been a great burden for North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7576 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas061__a94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-061-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Han Sung-chu Hopeful on PRC Role in DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003112994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 8--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3003112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] ROK Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu expressed his 
hopes about China's influence on the DPRK (North Korea) over 
that nation's alleged nuclear weapons development program. On 
29 March, Foreign Minister Han stopped over at Narita Airport on 
the way from Beijing to the United States, and during the brief 
stop, he met with a NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN correspondent at an 
airport hotel. He said that "we would like to place our hope on 
China's persuasive power with North Korea." Referring to his 
U.S. visit, he said that he intends to meet U.S. Government 
leaders to discuss the two nations' future stands toward North 
Korea. He added, in particular, that the U.S.- ROK 
consultations will focus on the possibility of UN Security 
Council resolutions against North Korea in line with the results 
of the Japanese-ROK and Chinese-ROK summit talks. 
  As for China's desirable role in the nuclear issue involving 
North Korea, Foreign Minister Han stated: "Just like Japan, 
China has an important role in this issue. We would like to 
place our hopes on China's persuasive power with North Korea, 
while we still do not know how effective this actually will be." 
  Foreign Minister Han had been visiting China as the deputy 
leader of the ROK delegation led by President Kim Yong-sam, and 
he is heading for the United States straightaway. After his 
U.S. visit, he is scheduled to again visit Japan on 3 April and 
to meet with Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and other Japanese 
leaders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

