<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura Pledges Trade Steps by `End of June' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003033294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0323 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003033294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 30 KYODO -- Japan will strive to come 
up with more concrete measures to further open its markets by 
the end of June to help conclude stalled bilateral trade talks 
with the United States, Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi 
Takemura said Wednesday. "It is enormously important for the 
Japanese Government to put all its energy into compiling such 
measures in June, because the U.S. is focusing on our June 
package," the top government spokesman told a news conference. 
  Takemura's comment came after U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor rejected as inadequate a fresh Japanese 
market-opening package unveiled Tuesday. "We have reviewed 
these measures and they do not meet (our) concerns," Kantor said 
at a White House news conference Tuesday. 
  Takemura said Kantor's negative assessment of the Japanese 
package is regrettable. But he also expressed hope for an early 
resumption of the stalemated "framework" trade negotiations 
saying he is paying attention to Kantor's remark suggesting 
there remain possibilities of resuming the bilateral trade talks 
if Japan makes further concessions. 
  Kantor said, "we are not discouraged. The Government of 
Japan has described this as a first step and we see it as a work 
in progress." 
  On Tuesday, Japan announced a set of market-opening measures 
designed primarily to pare down its lopsided trade surplus with 
the U.S., which amounted to some 60 billion dollars last year. 
  The package features tax cuts and other macroeconomic steps 
to spur domestic demand, market-opening measures in four sectors 
and voluntary overtures in three priority areas of the trade 
talks with the U.S. 
  The chief cabinet secretary denied that Tokyo plans to send 
a 
special envoy to Washington to officially explain Japan's 
efforts to boost foreign access to its markets and slash its 
trade surpluses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7583 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas061_a_94004" </HT>


