<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Strong Yen Affects Imported Goods' Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903121394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1100 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 29 KYODO -- The strong yen has been 
reflected in prices of imported goods, the Finance Ministry and 
the Economic Planning Agency (EPA) reported Tuesday [29 March]. 
The report, based on a survey of price movements in March, said 
import prices at customs clearance declined in 24 of 30 items 
surveyed, while retail prices dropped in 15 of 17 items. 
  Retail prices of imported beef dropped 14 percent, compared 
with February, it said. 
  EPA officials said the survey showed that the decline of 
import prices declared at customs clearance was reflected in 
retail prices. 
  The officials said prices of wine imported from France in 
February were down 37.8 percent compared with a year earlier. 
  Prices of frozen octopus and Italian-made dress shirts have 
declined around 30 percent from the year before, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7584 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas061_a_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-061 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Plans To Double Tourists To U.S. by 2000 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903053294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0439 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903053294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 29 KYODO -- The Transport Ministry on 
Tuesday [29 March] announced a plan to double the number of 
Japanese tourists to the United States to 6.8 million by 2000 as 
part of efforts to reduce Japan's swollen current account 
surplus with the U.S. Ministry officials said the government 
hopes to conduct negotiations with the U.S. on specific measures 
if Washington agrees to the plan. 
  Japan posted a tourism account deficit of 10 billion dollars 
with the U.S. in fiscal 1992, while recording a trade surplus of 
four times as much. 
  Under the plan, the tourism deficit is expected to double to 
20 billion dollars to help reduce Japan's current account 
surplus, the officials said. 
  The ministry had hoped to incorporate the plan in the 
package 
of macroeconomic measures the government announced earlier 
Tuesday to open Japan's markets and spur domestic demand, but 
failed to do so because of policy differences within the 
government, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

