<H3> <TI>   Hearings Planned on Housing Imports Regulations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903043194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0357 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 29 KYODO -- The Construction Ministry 
will conduct hearings on housing makers and other related 
industries on Japan's regulations on imports of houses and 
construction materials, Construction Minister Kozo Igarashi said 
Tuesday [29 March]. Igarashi told a press conference after the 
day's cabinet meeting that the ministry will call executives of 
housing makers, contractors, and trading houses in early April 
to hear their opinions on the restrictions. 
  The results of the hearings will be referred to when the 
ministry works out deregulatory steps in these areas. 
  Easing of the curbs on housing imports is viewed as a 
necessary step to bring down Japan's relatively expensive house 
building costs. The ministry has drafted an action plan to 
reduce the Japanese costs by one-third by 2000. 

