<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Over One-Third of Nation's Koreans in Chongnyon </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003123994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1114 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 30 KYODO -- More than one-third of 
about 680,000 Korean residents in Japan are members of the 
pro-Pyongyang General Association of Korean Residents in Japan 
(Chongnyon), the head of the Justice Ministry's Public Security 
Investigation Agency said Wednesday [30 March]. 
  Shigetake Ogata, speaking to the House of Representatives 
Budget Committee, said that about 247,000 Korean residents are 
Chongnyon members, including 56,000 in Chongnyon affiliates, 
while 369,000 are members of the pro-Seoul Korean Residents 
Union in Japan (Mindan). Ogata also said that 63,000 Korean 
residents profess to be neutral. 
  According to the Justice Ministry's Immigration Bureau, 
about 
688,000 Koreans were living in Japan in 1993. The agency 
determined the breakdown of statistics through figures provided 
by the agency's offices in each prefecture. 
  Regarding the sending of money to North Korea by 
pro-Pyongyang Korean residents, Ogata said that the residents 
send the money through a number of routes, including trade 
payments, remittances to relatives and friends in North Korea, 
and joint business ventures, and donations to the Korean Workers 
Party [Workers Party of Korea] and government organizations. He 
added that some of the money, estimated to be between 60 billion 
and 80 billion yen, is sent through banks or taken along by 
residents visiting North Korea. 
  The issue of Korean residents sending money to North Korea 
has gathered attention with increasing talk of economic 
sanctions against Pyongyang for refusing to permit full 
inspections of nuclear facilities suspected of being part of a 
secret atomic weapons plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

