<H3> <TI>   Policy-Making Study Group Plan Postponed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003001894 Tokyo KYODO in English 2342 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003001894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 30 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa's plan to form a policy study group involving all the 
ruling coalition partners will be put off to avoid a split in 
the coalition, according to political sources. A senior 
official of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], a key member of the 
seven-party coalition, said Tuesday night the party must rethink 
the proposal but said the basic concept has not changed. 
  A senior official of Komeito, another coalition party which 
backs the plan, also said the study group could not be formed at 
the present juncture. 
  Shinseito, Komeito and the Japan New Party led by Hosokowa 
have agreed to establish a policy study group next month with 
the aim of ultimately merging all of the coalition parties into 
a single party. 
  But Tomiichi Murayama, leader of the Social Democratic Party 
[of Japan] (SDP) [SDPJ], the largest force in the coalition, 
Tuesday expressed opposition to the plan. Murayama told 
reporters that if joining the study group is a condition to be 
selected as a joint candidate under the new electoral system for 
the House of Representatives or if the group is designed to 
create a new party, he "would not be able to agree" to let SDPJ 
legislators participate. 
  Democratic Socialist Party (DSP) Chairman Keigo Ouchi said 
Tuesday coalition members should not rush to join the study 
group, which he said is based on a scheme to create a new party. 
  "Joining the group as individuals could lead to a collapse 
of 
the political party," he said. "There is no chance that the DSP 
will participate in the group en masse under the current 
circumstances." 

</TEXT>

