<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition Decides Against Creating Unified Party </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003121194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1159 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 30 KYODO -- The ruling coalition on 
Wednesday decided to hold a fence-mending meeting of top 
officials in early April to repair strained relations among the 
partners after calling off a scheme for creating a new party, 
coalition sources said Wednesday. Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa's plan to establish a policy study group of coalition 
legislators as the launching pad for a new party was shelved 
after the scheme threatened to topple the fractious coalition. 
  Policy-making executives of the coalition partners set a 
meeting of representatives on Monday for improving soured 
relations among the coalition partners after the plan drew 
criticism from two of the seven ruling parties, the Social 
Democratic Party [SDP] and new party Sakigake [Harbinger]. 
  The plan was being ambitiously pursued by Hosokawa, along 
with the coalition's two strategists Ichiro Ozawa, secretary 
general of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], and Yuichi Ichikawa, 
secretary general of the Buddhist-backed Komeito [Clean 
Government Party]. 
  The study group would have set the stage for merging the 
seven coalition parties into a single party with possible 
participation by some members of the opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party. The coalition partners who had pushed for the 
plan pointed the need for closer policy coordination among the 
members. 
  Ichikawa, speaking at a meeting of Komeito legislators 
Wednesday, said, "There still remains the need to enhance the 
sense of policy unification among the coalition partners." 
"There will be no cooperation over elections without unity on 
policy," he said. 
  Shinseito's deputy secretary general, Kozo Watanabe, who 
spoke at a meeting of party executives the same day, called for 
a grouping that everybody can join freely. "We need to 
cooperate toward creating a united party," he said. 
  Takashi Yonezawa, general secretary of the Democratic 
Socialist Party (DSP), also a coalition partner, joined the 
chorus of calls for continued efforts toward creating a new 
party. 
  Yonezawa said the DSP should play an active role along with 
Hosokawa's Japan New Party and Sakigake in establishing a forum 
for discussing policy coordination in view of fielding joint 
candidates in coming national elections under the new election 
system. 
  The move toward a new party was accelerated after Hosokawa 
pushed through a political reform package in January, replacing 
multi-seat districts with single-seat constituencies in general 
election for the House of Representatives. 
  But the initiatives by Hosokawa, Ozawa and Ichikawa have met 
strong antagonism from the SDP, the largest bloc in the 
coalition, and new party Sakigake led by Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura. 
  Koken Nosaka, chairman of the SDP's Diet Affairs Committee, 
said at the meeting of top coalition officials that making 
participation in the proposed study group preconditioned on 
supporting joint coalition candidates for elections could lead 
to a split in the coalition. 
  Meanwhile, Toshio Yamaguchi, an independent member of the 
House of Representatives, who has been a major proponent for the 
scheme, said at a press conference that the plan for an 
interparty study group is still alive. He said he wants to 
start a preparatory committee for the group by the end of April. 
  But a senior Komeito member said, "The situation is already 
beyond the power of Mr. Yamaguchi." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

