<H3> <TI>   Ex-Kajima Company Official Indicted for Bribe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903121494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1053 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tokyo, March 29 KYODO -- Prosecutors indicted 
former Kajima Corp. Vice President Shinji Kiyoyama on Tuesday 
[29 March] on a charge of bribing a former Liberal Democratic 
Party (LDP) legislator to seek his influence in pressuring the 
Fair Trade Commission [FTC] over a bid-rigging case involving 
Kajima. The indictment said Kiyoyama handed over a 10 million 
yen bribe to former Construction Minister Kishiro Nakamura on 
January 13, 1992, asking him to pressure then FTC Chairman 
Setsuo Umezawa not to file a criminal accusation against a 
now-disbanded, 66-company "bid-rigging consultation" group in 
Saitama Prefecture, of which Kajima was a key member. 
  Nakamura, 44, was an acting chairman of the LDP's lobby of 
legislators concerning the Antimonopoly Law at the time he 
allegedly complied with Kiyoyama's request, it said. 
  Kiyoyama, 68, is currently standing trial on a separate 
charge of bribing Fujio Takeuchi, former governor of Ibaraki 
Prefecture, to secure his political influence in pressuring the 
local government to award a public works project to Kajima. 
  Kiyoyama's indictment over the FTC affair followed a 
decision 
earlier in the day by the nation's top prosecutors to indict 
both Nakamura and Kiyoyama on bribery charges, investigative 
sources said. However, the prosecutors decided to defer 
Nakamura's indictment until Friday, when his court-authorized 
20-day detention runs out, the sources said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

