<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Information Sectors Urge Tokyo To Buoy Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003040794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0347 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003040794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 30 KYODO -- Representatives of 
information-related industries on Wednesday [30 March] asked the 
government to carry out its economic stimulus measures promptly 
so as to help them out of the prolonged business slump. Leaders 
of the Electronic Industries Association of Japan (EIAJ) and 
four other sectors related to information, electronics and 
electrical machinery made the request during a breakfast meeting 
with Hiroshi Kumagai, international trade and industry minister. 
  Tadahiro Sekimoto, chairman of the EIAJ, while making a 
severe assessment of business conditions surrounding his 
industry, said the government should place top priority on 
stimulating the economy. 
  Takashi Kitaoka, chairman of the Japan Electronic Industry 
Development Association, sought an increased role by the 
government in upgrading the information infrastructure in Japan, 
particularly promotion of information networking. 
  The computer industry suffered a sharp setback in hardware 
production for the second consecutive year, Kitaoka said. 
  Kumagai said his ministry is maximizing efforts for an early 
recovery of Japanese business activity, for example, by 
formulating a program to create new business. But structural 
problems facing Japan's business sectors need to be solved 
first, Kumagai said, noting such problems are partly responsible 
for high material, personnel and production costs in Japan. 
  Tomoo Takahara, chairman of the Japan Information Service 
Industry Association, said the ailing software industry is 
pushing ahead with efficient relocation of white-collar workers 
and revamping of overall business operations. 

</TEXT>

