<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Large Retailers' Sales `Decreased' in Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903060394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0524 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903060394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 29 KYODO -- Sales at Japan's large 
retailers decreased 2.8 percent in February from a year earlier 
to 1,452.3 billion yen, the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry (MITI) said Tuesday [29 March]. It was the 21st 
straight month of falling sales at department stores and 
supermarket chains, the ministry said in a preliminary report. 
  The stagnant performance reflected continuing price 
consciousness among Japanese consumers, the ministry said. 
  Sales at 419 department stores across the nation dropped 4.4 
percent to 723.0 billion yen, for the 24th running month of 
declines from year-earlier levels, it said. Sales at 2,059 
supermarket chains edged down 1.0 percent to 729.4 billion yen, 
marking the 19th straight month of drops. 
  The 2.8 percent sales fall in February compares with a 2.5 
percent drop registered in January. 

</TEXT>

