<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Students Reported Resisting Market Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003110094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1030 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003110094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 30 (KCNA) -- One million students 
under the South Korean Federation of General Student Councils 
(Hanchongnyon) have risen up in a new struggle to check the 
"parliamentary ratification" of the "implementation schedule of 
the Uruguay Round accord" including rice market opening, 
according to a radio report from Seoul. 
  Students of 130 universities and colleges affiliated with 
Hanchongnyon decided to launch into various forms of struggle 
such as rallies, a signature campaign in streets and 
distribution of literatures in order to check the railroading of 
the "motion" on market opening at the "National Assembly" 
session which will begin on April 12. 
  It decided to hold a meeting of representatives at Pusan 
University in early April with the attendance of more than 
15,000 student representatives from all parts of South Korea and 
then go on a strike against the "parliamentary ratification" of 
the schedule. 
  It also decided to send students to the countryside to wage 
a 
joint struggle with farmers and expand the struggle in 
solidarity with trade unions in May. 

</TEXT>

