<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Expressions of Support Received From Abroad </TI></H3>
<H4>   From Malaysia, Congo, Senegal </H4>
<F P=102> SK3003010194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1032 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003010194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- Prime ministers of 
different countries voiced full support for the just cause of 
the Korean people. 
  Malaysian Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr. Mahathir bin-Mohamed 
met a special envoy of the great leader President Kim Il-song on 
March 25. He said the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula 
should be resolved through negotiation and it was impossible to 
solve it by means of pressure. 
  Supporting a peaceful solution to the Korean reunification 
question, he said that if Korea were reunified, it would become 
the strongest country in the world. 
  The Congolese Prime Minister Jacques Joachim Yhombi-Opango, 
when he received a delegation of the Foreign Ministry of the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea on March 25, said the 
nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula should be resolved through 
dialogue and negotiation. 
  Hoping that Korea would be reunified independently by 
confederacy formula without foreign interference, as indicated 
by the great leader his excellency President Kim Il-song, he 
declared that the Congolese people's feelings of fraternal 
friendship with the Korean people would never change. 
  Senegalese Prime Minister Habib Thiam, when he received the 
DPRK Foreign Ministry delegation on March 24, expressed support 
for the proposal to reunify Korea by confederacy formula. 
  Noting that the nuclear issue of the Korean peninsula could 
not be resolved by means of pressure and threat, he expressed 
the hope that the issue would be solved through DPRK-U.S. talks. 

</TEXT>

