<H3> <TI>   Expressions of Support Received From Abroad </TI></H3>
<H4>   From Madagascar, Uganda, Ghana </H4>
<F P=102> SK3003044694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0431 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003044694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Military Threat to and Pressure on DPRK Condemned" -- KCNA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 30 (KCNA) -- Political parties and 
organizations of different countries have expressed support to 
the March 21 statement of a DPRK Foreign Ministry spokesman as 
regards the fact that the United States is aggravating the 
situation of the Korean peninsula after breaking off the 
DPRK-U.S. talks. 
  The Party of the Congress for the Independence, the Militant 
Party for the Realization of Equality and nine other political 
parties of Madagascar published a joint statement on March 23. 
  Noting that the United States is leading the situation of 
the 
Korean peninsula to the extreme pitch of strain after reversing 
the agreed conclusions reached at the DPRK-U.S. contact in New 
York, the statement said: "The step taken by the DPRK to cope 
with this is a just one for national sovereignty and security." 
  Eight organizations of Uganda including the Uganda-DPRK 
Friendship Association, the Ugandan National Committee for the 
Study of the Chuche Idea and the Teachers' Association of Uganda 
said in a joint statement on March 22: 
  "The United States has set unreasonable preconditions 
alleging that the inspection by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency was unsatisfactory. This was motivated by their 
insidious political aim to stifle socialist Korea by 
intentionally aggravating the situation." 
  The Ghana-DPRK Friendship Association said in a statement on 
March 22: 
  "We urge the United States to stop its threat and row of 
`sanctions' against the DPRK and sincerely discharge its 
obligation for a package solution to the nuclear issue and the 
IAEA secretariat to take a fair stand, not following the will of 
a big power." 
  Twenty-three political parties and organizations of Peru 
including the Mariateguista United Party and the General 
Confederation of Workers in a joint statement denounced the 
United States for reversing the agreed conclusions reached at 
the DPRK-U.S. contact in New York and scheming to stage the 
"Team Spirit" joint military exercises and deploy "Patriot" 
missiles in South Korea. 
  The statement called upon political parties, organizations 
and public figures throughout the world to strengthen solidarity 
with the Korean people in the efforts for peace and 
reunification. 

</TEXT>

