<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   KCNA Reports Increase in Textile Output </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003011794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1505 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003011794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 29 (KCNA) -- Textile output is 
moving upward in Korea. 
  According to data available at the General Bureau of Textile 
Industry, it grew 30 percent in the first two months of this 
year or more above the same period last year. The output in 20 
odd days of March was 2.4 million metres more than that in the 
same period last month. That period in March witnessed a 19 
percent gain in spinning yarn output. 
  Korea meets the demand of the population for textiles with 
home products from long ago. 
  With his scientific penetration into the limitation of 
cotton 
production and favourable condition of chemical fibre production 
in the country, the great leader President Kim Il-song put 
forward a wise policy of building an independent and modern 
textile industry by correctly combining textile industrial 
branches using chemical fibre with those using other fibres, 
with stress laid on the former. And he set forth a policy of 
developing large scale central industry and medium- and 
small-sized local industry in parallel and has wisely led the 
work for its implementation. 
  Today the nation's textile industry has developed into a 
versatile and mighty industry with chemical fibre, cotton, wool 
and silk textile sectors, which are equipped with uptodate 
technology and firmly rely on domestic raw materials. 
  Hundreds of large and minor spinning and textile mills are 
operating in Pyongyang, Sinuiju, Sariwon, Hamhung and other 
parts of the country. 30 metres of textiles went to each head 
of the population already in 1970 in the country where per 
capita textile output was 14 centimetres before the liberation 
in August 1945. The annual textile output jumped to more than 
800 million metres in the Second Seven-Year Plan period 
(1978-1984). 
  In the period of the Third Seven-Year Plan (1987-1993), 
modern and high-speed textile equipment was introduced and new 
equipment was installed at the Pyongyang textile combine and the 
Kusong, Sariwon and Kaesong textile mills, laying a solid 
foundation for sharply increasing textile output. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

