<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Rejects North's Proposals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003084094 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0700 GMT 30 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK3003084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yi Kwang-tok from Washington] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu said that the third 
round of U.S.-North Korean talks will be held only if North 
Korea accepts additional inspections by a International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA] team and complies with a North-South 
dialogue. In addition, he has refused North Korea's recent 
proposals to discuss the issue of the additional inspections at 
the third U.S.-North Korean talks. 
  Foreign Minister Han, who is now staying in Washington to 
seek joint measures for resolving the North Korean nuclear 
issue, made those remarks prior to a meeting with U.S. Secretary 
of State Christopher. He added that if North Korea does not 
accept the IAEA's request for additional inspections, the 
international community, including the United Nations, will have 
no choice other than imposing sanctions on North Korea. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu said that if North Korea does 
not change its attitude but instead strongly reacts to the 
international community by withdrawing from the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty, the international community, including 
the ROK, the United States, and the United Nations, will respond 
strongly. 
  Foreign Minister Han said: During the ROK-PRC summit talks 
and the ROK-PRC foreign ministers' talks, China stressed that it 
would exercise influence over North Korea only if a phase of 
North-South dialogue continues. China has also asked the ROK 
side to create an atmosphere in which China can fully play a 
role in resolving the nuclear issue. 
  In addition, Foreign Minister Han said that he would meet 
with U.S. Secretary of State Christopher to discuss if the UN 
Security Council will adopt a statement in the name of its 
president or adopt a resolution. He stressed that if the UN 
Security Council adopts the statement, it will include the 
deadline for North Korean nuclear inspections and additional 
steps at the UN level. Foreign Minister Han is expected to meet 
UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali and representatives of 
the permanent member states of the UN Security Council on 31 
March and ask for their cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

