<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supports `Stronger' Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003081594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0734 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003081594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 29 (YONHAP) -- Seoul and 
Washington will be coordinating the form and tone of the U.N. 
Security Council message on the North Korean nuclear wrangle at 
Thursday's [31 March] foreign ministers' meeting. 
  Visiting South Korean Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu meets 
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, and sources say they 
are likely to agree on issuing a statement by the council 
president rather than adopting a resolution -- but carrying the 
same strength in tone. 
  Han told Korean reporters that if the council opts for a 
presidential statement, all permanent members including China 
will speak in favor with North Korea the only country opposing 
it. 
  "This will make public the fact that China is on our side," 
Han said. 
  But he suggested that the tone of the statement should be 
stronger than what China has proposed, putting in print the 
deadline by when North Korea should allow international 
inspection of its nuclear facilities and a warning on sanctions 
if Pyongyang fails to comply. 
  On whether Seoul and Washington would resume their joint 
military maneuvers, Team Spirit, Han said the United States has 
always respected Seoul's position and decisions. 
  "This time, we would be asking what Washington thinks 
instead 
of consulting them on our own position," Han said. 

</TEXT>

