<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Difficulty Expected in UNSC Accord on DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003020594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0154 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003020594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 29 (YONHAP) -- The UN Security 
Council may not be able to secure a result at Thursday's session 
on the North Korean nuclear problem due to a dispute between 
China and the four other permanent members, sources here said 
Tuesday. 
  The presidential statement demanded by China significantly 
tones down the message and excludes an inspection deadline and 
any mention of possible sanctions, they said. 
  A closed-door session is scheduled for Thursday at the 
United 
Nations, where the United States may decide to push for a 
resolution as it first planned, according to the sources. 
  The council had been expected to reach a final agreement at 
Thursday's session, but that may be impossible due to the 
dispute among its members, they said. 
  The U.S.-proposed draft resolution gives North Korea one 
month to accept inspections by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) and warns of "further steps" if Pyongyang refuses, 
referring to economic sanctions. 
  China has opposed such a resolution and proposed a 
presidential statement instead. 

</TEXT>

