<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK UN Mission on Resuming U.S. Dialogue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003074094 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0705 GMT 30 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK3003074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kim Chin-ha from UN Headquarters in New York] </F>
  [Text] On 30 March North Korea proposed resuming dialogue 
with the United States to resolve the present deadlocked nuclear 
issue. A spokesman from the North Korean mission to the United 
Nations said in a statement that North Korea wants to resolve 
the nuclear issue by dialogue, not by armed forces. In 
particular, it expects the issue to be settled within the 
framework of proposals made by President Clinton in his news 
conference on 24 March. 
  In his news conference held last week, President Clinton 
said 
that the United States wants to maintain normal relations with 
North Korea and that if North Korea abides by the international 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, its future will be brighter. 
  Quoting remarks by a North Korean diplomat, THE NEW YORK 
TIMES also reported today that unofficial working-level contacts 
between the United States and North Korea are presently being 
held at the United Nations, and that an official channel has 
also been opened between the United States and North Korea. 
  The paper reported, however, that a U.S. envoy to the United 
Nations and a spokesman for the U.S. State Department had 
strongly denied the rumors regarding the U.S.-North Korean 
contacts. 

</TEXT>

