<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Dropping of Preconditions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003033194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0252 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003033194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 29 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has 
indirectly proposed that it will allow International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) checks of seven nuclear facilities only 
after a third round of high-level talks with the United States. 
  One senior official at the North Korean Mission to the 
United 
Nations in New York said Tuesday that the original agreements 
reached between North Korea and the United States and North 
Korea and the IAEA called for a comprehensive IAEA inspection of 
only five of the seven sites. 
  As for the other two facilities -- a 5-megawatt reactor and 
a 
radiochemical laboratory -- North Korea had agreed to accept 
IAEA inspections that are necessary only to maintain continuity 
in nuclear safeguards, the official claimed. 
  The question of permitting comprehensive IAEA inspections of 
all seven facilities in North Korea, a member of the nuclear 
non- proliferation treaty (NPT), must be resolved at the third 
round of high-level talks between Pyongyang and Washington, he 
said. 
  The official, who declined to be identified by name, said 
the 
United States is reportedly planning to raise the question of 
special checks of the two facilities at the talks. 
  The U.S. position mirrors that of a hostile country 
demanding 
that the other side publicly disclose its military technology, 
the official said. He thus ruled out the possibility that the 
IAEA may conduct special inspections. 
  The official also demanded that the United States not attach 
any preconditions to further dialogue. 
  "The United States has to give up the idea that U.S.-North 
Korean talks are some kind of present (to Pyongyang)," he said. 
"In fact, we do not feel an urgent need for dialogue with the 
United States." 
  The official's comments confirm widely held suspicions that 
much time and effort are needed to resolve the issue since South 
Korea, the United States and their allies are demanding that 
North Korea permit IAEA inspections immediately while Pyongyang 
is seeking further talks with Washington first. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

