<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul, PRC To Increase Technical Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2803130994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1200 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2803130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 28 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and China on 
Monday agreed to make joint studies for environmental protection 
and undertake other schemes to beef up bilateral technical 
cooperation. 
  An official at the Ministry of Science and Technology said 
the agreement was made at a meeting in Beijing between South 
Korean Science and Technology Minister Kim Si-chung and his 
Chinese counterpart, Song Jian, minister of the State Science 
and Technology Commission. 
  Minister Kim was in Beijing as a member of the official 
suite 
of President Kim Yong-sam presently on a state visit to China. 
  As an initial project of joint environmental programs, the 
two countries would soon inaugurate a joint Yellow Sea study 
team to work out ways to control Yellow Sea contamination. 
  In the aeronautical area, South Korea and China would 
jointly 
develop knowhow on airplane design with a view to producing 
mid-sized airplanes in a joint scheme. 
  Also at Monday's meeting, the two ministers decided to 
exchange 30 technicians between their countries this year 
instead of 15 and step up cooperation in the area of elementary 
science. 
  They further agreed to conclude a Korea-China atomic energy 
agreement and an atomic energy safeguards memorandum at the 
second Korea-China joint Science and Technology Committee 
meeting slated for October this year in Seoul, the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

