<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Il-song Badge No Longer on Official Lapels </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003080094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0743 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 30 (YONHAP) -- The ubiquitous badge 
featuring North Korean President Kim Il-song has disappeared 
from the lapels of North Korean officials attending 
international conferences, fueling speculation as to what it 
signifies. 
  Rep. Pak Chung-su, who led a South Korean delegation to the 
91st International Parliamentary Union (IPU) meeting in Paris, 
said Wednesday he noticed that all nine members of the North 
Korean delegation had not sported the Kim Il-song badge. 
  In addition, all six North Korean representatives at another 
Paris meeting of the United Nations Educational, Social and 
Cultural Organization (UNESCO) did not wear the badge, according 
to Pak. 
  The absence of the badge, the symbol of Kim Il-song's 
"chuche" (self-reliance) ideology, is drawing unusual attention 
because all North Korean officials had until recently worn it as 
though it were a bodily appendage, Pak said. 
  "It is a big change, considering the rigidity and 
inflexibility of the North Korean regime and society," Pak added. 
  Pak speculated that North Korea's leaders may be preparing 
"a 
grace period" during a transition of power from Kim Il-song to 
his son and heir-apparent, Kim Chong-il. 

</TEXT>

