<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leader Denies DPRK Visit Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3003081994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0653 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3003081994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 30 (YONHAP) -- Democratic Party 
chairman Yi Ki-taek on Wednesday refuted a recent North Korean 
statement expressing hope that he would soon visit Pyongyang, 
indicating he has no such plans at this juncture. 
  "They (North Koreans) might have something to give me, but 
they needn't tell me to do this or that," he said. 
  A close associate said Yi thinks it undesirable to visit 
North Korea when the nuclear issue remains so touchy. "But there 
is no change in his plans to visit North Korea to help establish 
smooth inter-Korean relations when an opportune time comes 
along," the associate added. 
  On Tuesday, an unidentified spokesman for North Korea's 
Supreme People's Assembly (parliament) issued a statement saying 
the speaker's invitation for Yi to visit Pyongyang is still open. 
  The ruling Democratic Liberal Party also criticized the 
North 
Korean statement for its hidden motive to create confusion in 
South Korean politics. 

</TEXT>

