<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Market-Opening Package Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Package Termed Significant Step </H4>
<F P=102> OW3003030894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0257 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003030894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 30 KYODO -- A new Japanese package of 
market-opening measures is a "significant step" in trade 
negotiations with the United States, despite U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor's grim assessment of the plan, a 
government source said Wednesday [30 March]. The source was 
commenting on Kantor's overnight comments in Washington that the 
measures, announced in Tokyo on Tuesday, do not meet U.S. 
concerns on bilateral trade issues ranging from auto trade to 
government procurement. 
  The source also stressed that Japan expects to announce an 
additional market-opening package in June for presentation at 
the Group of Seven (G-7) summit of industrial nations set for 
July in Naples, Italy. He also expressed hope that the latest 
package will lead to a resumption of bilateral "framework" trade 
talks that broke down in mid-February. 

</TEXT>

