<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   NTT on Procurement Policy for Foreign Firms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903101694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0936 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 29 KYODO -- Nippon Telegraph and 
Telephone Corp. (NTT) said Tuesday [29 March] it will review its 
procurement policy under a 1981 Japan-U.S. agreement as part of 
efforts to increase foreign companies' opportunities for 
NTT-related business. 
  Japan's telecommunications giant privatized in 1985 will 
improve its procedures for buying components and other products 
for use in equipment to facilitate foreign companies' access to 
NTT business, a company spokesman said. 
  Specifically, NTT will provide prospective bidders with 
information on its procurement plans before they are unveiled in 
the government's official gazettes, the spokesman said. At 
present, such information can be obtained only after specific 
procurement plans are made public in the gazettes. 
  The latest step follows a U.S. request that the Japanese 
Government treat NTT purchases as part of its procurements. The 
government has rejected the request, saying that NTT "is 
basically a private business," not a government agency. 
  The 1981 pact calls for nondiscriminatory treatment of 
foreign bidders by NTT in its procurement policy. "NTT will 
maximize its efforts to respond to foreign demand," the 
spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

