<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Prepare Fully for DPRK Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3103081494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 31 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3103081494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] During a session of the House of Representatives 
Budget Committee on 30 March, Taro Nakayama of the opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party asked Prime Minister Hosokawa how the 
government will deal with economic sanctions against North 
Korea, which is suspected of developing nuclear weapons, if the 
UN Security Council votes to impose sanctions on it. In response 
to the question, the prime minister said, "Each ministry and 
agency is now studying the concrete ways possible within its 
administrative jurisdiction to deal with the economic 
sanctions." The prime minister also stressed that "Japan will 
have to carry out complete preparations." In this way, the 
prime minister made it clear that the government is now studying 
a wide range of measures to deal with the economic sanctions and 
to maintain public peace and order in Japan. 
  During the session, Sadao Yamahana, the minister in charge 
of 
political reform from the Social Democratic Party, was asked how 
he will deal with the issue of North Korea's nuclear development 
program. In response, Mr. Yamahana echoed the prime minister's 
statement, saying, "As a cabinet member, I will deal with the 
issue in a responsible manner within the limits of the 
Constitution." 
  Testifying before the session, Shigetake Ogata, Public 
Security Investigation Agency director general, stated, "Of the 
ethnic Koreans residing in Japan, approximately 247,000 have 
some relationship with the General Association of Korean 
Residents in Japan, and approximately 56,000 of them are 
formally affiliated with the pro-North Korean organization in 
Japan." As for the amount of their remittances to North Korea, 
Mr. Ogata said, "We possess no accurate measure of the 
remittances," but he added, "rumors have it that the amount 
ranges from 60 billion yen to 80 billion yen a year." [passage 
omitted on Hosokawa's acceptance of a loan from the Sagawa 
Kyubin company] 

</TEXT>

