<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Automakers Worry About Voluntary Target Outcome </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003135394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3003135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As of 29 March, five major Japanese automakers have 
formulated their plans to increase purchases of foreign auto 
parts in particular. In their plans, the automakers came up 
with financial targets concerning their purchases, because they 
took into account the ongoing bilateral frictions over the 
automobile sector. In trying desperately to avoid having their 
targets be considered commitments, however, automakers are 
trying to put across their individual plans through such means 
as setting different fiscal years as their respective target 
periods. While praising such efforts by the private sector, the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI] remains very 
sensitive to how the United States will now respond, saying that 
"the atmosphere in Washington is quite severe" (as stated by a 
top MITI official). 
  Although the five automakers' procurement plans cover all 
overseas products, they focus primarily on importing more auto 
parts and completely assembled automobiles from the United 
States. Automakers have avoided disclosing their data on past 
purchases, and they have also set different fiscal years as 
target periods. However, if we dare add up all the figures 
listed in the automakers' finalized purchase plans, the total 
purchases of auto parts come to approximately $23 billion. 
  This figure surpasses the target figure of $17.8 billion 
which the five automakers had to share and meet when it was 
announced during U.S. President George Bush's visit to Japan in 
1992 that Japan would "purchase $19 billion worth of auto parts 
in fiscal year 1994." However, the figure falls far short of 
the expectations of the U.S. automobile industry, which is 
"demanding a 30-percent annual increase." Consequently, 
concerns have been voiced doubting the effectiveness of the 
latest voluntary purchase plans in resolving the bilateral 
automobile trade dispute. 
  However, there are some advantages for Japanese makers of 
fully assembled automobiles to purchase U.S. auto parts. Among 
crucial parts, for example, antilock braking systems (ABS) "made 
in the United States are 80 percent less expensive than those 
made in Japan" (as stated by a Toyota Motor Corporation 
official). 
  On the backdrop of the yen's appreciation against the dollar 
and the recovery of U.S. auto parts manufacturers, Japanese 
automaker officials recently confessed that "if we really wanted 
to, there are many U.S. auto parts that we could buy." 
  The problem, however, is that automobile exports -- which 
have been the mainstay of the Japanese automobile industry -- 
are continuing to drop. Due to declining exports, the domestic 
production of automobiles by the Honda Motor Company, Ltd. is 
expected to drop from 1.2 million units in 1992 to around 1.06 
million units in 1994. 
  Because the outlook is also uncertain for domestic 
automobile 
sales, automakers find it difficult to boldly announce plans to 
import more auto parts. While maintaining that "there may be 
adjustments in automobile production" (as stated by a Mazda 
Motor Corporation official), automakers express strong concerns 
that their voluntary target figures may assume lives of their 
own and become commitments. 
  Meanwhile, it is expected that the United States will now 
ask 
Japan to sell more fully assembled U.S. automobiles in its 
markets rather than U.S. auto parts because this would lead to a 
more direct increase in profits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7696 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas062__a94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-062-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Executives Polled on U.S. Summit, Market Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003145394 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3003145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] An ASAHI SHIMBUN opinion poll which surveyed 100 
major companies has revealed that most business executives 
regarded the breakdown of the Japan-U.S. summit on the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks as "unavoidable." 
Meanwhile, concerning the voluntary market-opening package 
aimed at cutting the trade surplus which the government will 
formulate within this month, most executives noted a need to 
formulate concrete measures to ease regulations and expand 
domestic demand, including tax cuts and increased public 
investment. 
  In reply to a question on the Japan-U.S. summit breakdown, 
executives of 67 companies stated, "It was regrettable, but for 
the sake of building new bilateral relations it could not have 
been avoided." Only three answered, "It was only natural 
because the U.S. demand was unreasonable." In the meanwhile, 
only four executives answered that "Japan should have 
compromised." 
  What is noteworthy is that as many as 26 executives gave 
other answers, and most of them pointed out that the government 
had failed to make sufficient efforts to establish a "mature 
relationship." For example, several chemical company executives 
said, "What the government should have done was not only to 
reject U.S. demands but also to present alternative plans for 
cutting the trade surplus while taking the other side's position 
into consideration." 
  The results of the poll have revealed companies' strong 
hopes 
for the market-opening package now being formulated by the 
government. A financial company's executive said, "It is 
desirable that the government indicate definite measures to cut 
the trade surplus." Executives of 81 companies requested that 
"demand be expanded by taking such microeconomic measures as tax 
cuts and increased public investment." Also, executives from 71 
companies called on the government to include in the package 
"concrete goals to achieve deregulation and to correct the gap 
in prices between goods at home and abroad." 

</TEXT>

