<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   JNP, DSP Consider New Parliamentary Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3103081794 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3103081794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Executives of the Japan New Party [JNP] and the 
Democratic Socialist Party [DSP] met at a Tokyo restaurant on 
the evening of 29 March. During the meeting, both sides agreed 
that "the JNP, the DSP and Sakigake [Harbinger] share the same 
political beliefs and policies," and they proposed that as a 
first step toward realigning the current political parties "the 
three ruling parties form a unified parliamentary group in the 
House of Representatives." 
  The JNP and the DSP are trying to play a mediatory role 
between the ruling coalition parties and to look for a way to 
rally the ruling coalition parties to field their unified 
candidates in the next general election at a time when Shinseito 
[Japan Renewal Party], Komeito, and the Social Democratic Party 
of Japan are increasingly feuding over a plan for a policy 
research council. 
  Present at the meeting were five legislators from the JNP, 
including Secretary General Masuo Matsuoka, and five legislators 
from the DSP, including Secretary General Takashi Yonezawa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

